  "prompt": "What is Energy band?",
  "response": "An energy band is a range of energy levels in a solid where electrons can exist. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Definition:\n- A continuous range of energy levels that electrons can occupy in a solid\n- Represents the allowed energy states for electrons in a crystal lattice\n\n2. Types of Energy Bands:\n- Valence Band: Energy levels occupied by electrons in the outermost shell\n- Conduction Band: Energy levels where electrons can move freely\n- Forbidden Band (Energy Gap): Region between valence and conduction bands where electrons cannot exist\n\n3. Key Characteristics:\n- Formed due to interaction between atomic energy levels\n- Determines electrical and optical properties of materials\n- Width depends on atomic structure and bond type\n\n4. Classification Based on Band Structure:\n- Conductors: Overlapping valence and conduction bands\n- Semiconductors: Small energy gap between bands\n- Insulators: Large energy gap between bands\n\n5. Significance:\n- Explains electrical conductivity\n- Determines material's electronic properties\n- Important in understanding semiconductor physics\n- Crucial for designing electronic devices\n\n6. Formation:\n- Results from quantum mechanical interactions\n- Occurs when atoms are closely packed in a crystal\n\nUnderstanding energy bands helps explain how materials conduct electricity and behave electronically.",
